In conclusion, let me anticipate an objection which will no doubt be raised against the practice of imbed- ding pieces of translation in the notes to an author. In the first place slight difficulties are often explained more clearly by a translation than by a note, but, more than this, I shall hardly be accused of undertaking the defence of all Bolin's series when Ι give it as my firm belief that an accurate translation never yet injured a boy's scholarship. With ordinary care on the part of a master it need never screen an indolent Pupil, while it is often a great encouragement to a pains- taking boy whose work is just too difficult for him, and saves him from numberless misconceptions of an author's meaning, which, if accepted as first impressions‚ are afterwards so difficult to correct.
